{"title_page": "Lisa Wilson-Foley", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lisa Wilson-Foley\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| citizenship        = [[United States]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Ithaca College]]<br>[[Yale University]]<br>[[University of Connecticut]]\n| occupation         = Entrepreneur\n| party              = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse             = Brian Foley\n| children           = Multiple\n| net worth          = US$23 million (2010)\n}}\n\n'''Lisa Wilson-Foley''' (born approximately 1960) is an entrepreneur, former political candidate, and white collar criminal from the American state of [[Connecticut]]. A serial entrepreneur, she formed her first company at 29; she now owns rehabilitation company Allstar Therapy, family entertainment business Blue Fox Enterprises, and medical testing company Swallowing Diagnostics.\n\n== Early life and family ==\nWilson-Foley graduated from [[Farmington High School (Connecticut)|Farmington High School]] in 1977.<ref name=\"Linkedin\" /> Wilson-Foley received a B.S. from Ithaca College in 1981, a masters in Public Health from Yale University 1988, and a degree in Executive Managed Care Division from the University of Connecticut in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet the candidate: Lisa Wilson-Foley |url=https://archives.rep-am.com/2010/08/24/meet-the-candidate-lisa-wilson-foley/ |website=rep-am.com |publisher=Republican American |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> She received her doctorate from University of Montana in 2013. She met her husband Brian Foley while in grad school; he was one of her professors.<ref name=\"Sink Or Swim\"/> Together they have a blended family with seven children.<ref name=\"Watchdog News Hour Interview\" />\n\n== Business career ==\nA serial entrepreneur she formed her first company at 29.<ref name=\"Sink Or Swim\">{{cite book |last1=Priscilla Cale |first1=David C. Tate |title=Sink Or Swim: How Lessons from the Titanic Can Save Your Family Business |date=2011 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |location=Santa Barbara, California |isbn=9780313398346 |pages=140\u2013141}}</ref> In 1997 she sold her original healthcare businesses and as a result of an agreement she was prohibited from re-entering the healthcare field for several years. This forced her to pursue investments in the entertainment field.<ref name=\"Courant 1998\">{{cite web |last1=H. Johnson |first1=Paul |title=A PLACE TO ROCK 'N BOWL |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-1998-02-17-9802170467-story.html |website=www.courant.com |publisher=The Hartford Courant |accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref> She is also involved in her husband's businesses.  At the time of her conviction her personal net worth was estimated to be US$23 million, this is separate from her husband's nine figure net worth.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leigh Cowan |first1=Alison |title=Wilson-Foley given 5-month jail term |url=https://ctmirror.org/2015/03/24/lisa-wilson-foley-gets-5-month-jail-term/ |website=ctmirror.org |publisher=CT Mirror |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622114535/http://ctmirror.org/2015/03/24/lisa-wilson-foley-gets-5-month-jail-term/ |archive-date=22 June 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Many of her businesses are owned through her [[holding company]] LWF Holdings. Her friend [[Janet Peckinpaugh]] served as the marketing director of LWF Holdings.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hebert |first1=Gregory |title=Blue Fox Rock'n Bowl Cuts Ribbon on Laser Tag Arena |url=https://patch.com/connecticut/simsbury/blue-fox-rock-n-bowl-cuts-ribbon-on-laser-tag-arena |website=patch.com |publisher=Patch |accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> In 2010 her campaign claimed that she directly employed 500 people and had hosted a group of 15 Kenyan entrepreneurs on a tour of Connecticut.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wilson-Foley |title=Lisa Wilson-Foley, Candidate for Lieutenant Governor, Hosts 15 Kenyan Entrepreneurs |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/lisa-wilson-foley-candidate-for-lieutenant-governor-hosts-15-kenyan-entrepreneurs-92491829.html |website=prnewswire.com |publisher=Wilson-Foley 2010 |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Allstar Therapy===\nAllstar Therapy provides occupational, speech and physical rehabilitation in health care facilities throughout Connecticut, Massachusetts and Rhode Island. Allstar Therapy was sold in 2016.<ref name=\"Linkedin\">{{cite web |title=Lisa Wilson Foley |url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/lisa-wilson-foley-2a285b3 |website=www.linkedin.com |publisher=Linkedin |accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Blue Fox Enterprises === \nIn 1998 she acquired the Simsbury Bowling Center and renamed it Blue Fox Rock 'N Bowl and renovated  it emphasize a family friendly atmosphere.<ref name=\"Courant 1998\" /> In 1999 she acquired the Copper Hill Golf Club for $1.3m renaming it Fox Run at Copper Hill.<ref name=\"Courant 1999\">{{cite web |last1=Lemos |first1=Phil |title=GOLF COURSE GETS A NEW OWNER |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-1999-01-15-9901150564-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=The Hartford Courant |accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> The club was sold in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jensen |first1=Tim |title=West Suffield Resident Breathing New Life Into Copper Hill Golf Club |url=https://patch.com/connecticut/suffield/west-suffield-resident-breathing-new-life-into-copper-hill-golf-club |website=patch.com |publisher=Patch |accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref> The company recently sold three Victorian Bed and Breakfasts in [[Newport, RI]].<ref name=\"Linkedin\" /> \n\n==== Blue Fox Run Golf Course ====\nBlue Fox Run is a 27-hole golf course owned by Wilson-Foley notable for being the first in the country to offer onsite [[childcare]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lisa Wilson-Foley - Republican candidate for Lieutenant Governor |url=https://www.registercitizen.com/news/article/Lisa-Wilson-Foley-12112196.php |website=registercitizen.com |publisher=Hearst Media |accessdate=23 April 2019|date=2010-08-07 }}</ref> In 1996 she purchased the property, then known as the Bel Compo Golf Course and having only 18 holes, for US$3.5m with her husband purchasing 55 adjoining acres.<ref name=\"Courant 1996\">{{cite web |last1=Stowe |first1=Stacey |title=AVON PAIR TO BUY BEL COMPO COURSE |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-1996-09-30-9609300413-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=The Hartford Courant |accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref> In 1997 Wilson-Foley successfully applied to rezone 15 of their acres to office park, the parcel was subsequently developed with three office buildings having been built as of 2012.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sawyer |first1=Jessie |title=Commission Rejects Golf Club's Proposal to Rezone Open Space Land |url=https://patch.com/connecticut/avon/1m-homes-may-be-built-on-excess-avon-golf-club-land |website=patch.com |publisher=Patch |accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Hartford FoxForce ===\nIn 1999 Wilson-Foley and her husband franchised the [[World TeamTennis]] team Hartford FoxForce in [[Hartford, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bailer |first1=Darice |title=Team Tennis Finds a Home in Hartford |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/07/23/nyregion/team-tennis-finds-a-home-in-hartford.html?searchResultPosition=19 |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=26 April 2019|date=2000-07-23 }}</ref> FoxForce's first drafted player was [[Monica Seles]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Garber |first1=Greg |title=SELES FIRST MEMBER OF FOXFORCE |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2000-04-04-0004051707-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> In 2001 the team fielded brothers [[Murphy Jensen]] and [[Luke Jensen]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Roberto |title=FOXFORCE PUT JENSENS TOGETHER |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2001-04-12-0104122097-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=The Hartford Courant |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> Over the years the team fielded other well known players such as [[Bethanie Mattek-Sands]], [[Boris Becker]], and [[James Blake (tennis)|James Blake]]. The team played first at Hartford's 3,000 seat [[State Arsenal and Armory]] and later at a 2,500 seat outdoor stadium Wilson-Foley had built at her Blue Fox Run golf course. The Foley's shut the team down in 2007 due to a lack of corporate sponsorships.<ref>{{cite web |title=2000-2006 Hartford FoxForce |url=https://funwhileitlasted.net/2014/02/16/2000-2006-hartford-foxforce/ |website=funwhileitlasted.net |publisher=funwhileitlasted.net |accessdate=27 April 2019|date=2014-02-16 }}</ref> Mark Foley's [[Connecticut Pride]] also used the State Arsenal and Armory as a venue from 1993-2000.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hasty|first1=Roy|title=Connecticut Pride; Lion To Be King Where Hellcats Once Ruled|url=http://articles.courant.com/1995-08-11/sports/9508110481_1_aetna-life-casualty-tyler-jones-hartford-s-continental-basketball-association|accessdate=April 30, 2019|work=Hartford Courant|date=August 11, 1995|location=Hartford, Connecticut}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nBefore her conviction Wilson-Foley served as the vice-chair of the board at [[The Bushnell Center for the Performing Arts]].<ref name= \"Watchdog News Hour Interview\">{{cite web |last1=George |first1=Gombassy |title=Watchdog News Hour: Lisa Wilson-Foley |url=http://ctwatchdog.com/health/watchdog-news-hour-lisa-wilson-foley |website=ctwatchdog.com |publisher=CT Watchdog |accessdate=23 April 2019|date=2011-05-16 }}</ref> Previously she served on the board of the [[Renbrook School]] and the [[American School for the Deaf]].<ref name=\"Watchdog News Hour Interview\" />\n\n== Political campaigns ==\nShe is a political protege of former [[Governor of Connecticut]] [[John G. Rowland]] who called her \u201cgrasshopper\u201d during his political tutelage.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leigh Cowan |first1=Alison |title=Wilson-Foley given 5-month jail term |url=https://ctmirror.org/2015/03/24/lisa-wilson-foley-gets-5-month-jail-term/ |website=ctmirror.org |publisher=CT Mirror |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622114535/http://ctmirror.org/2015/03/24/lisa-wilson-foley-gets-5-month-jail-term/ |archive-date=22 June 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\n=== Lieutenant Governor ===\nIn 2010 Lisa Wilson-Foley announced that she was running for [[Lieutenant Governor of Connecticut]] as a Republican.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stewart |first1=Christine |title=Republican Announces For Lt. Gov. |url=https://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/archives/entry/republican_announces_for_lt._gov/ |website=ctnewsjunkie.com |publisher=CT News Junkie |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> Wilson-Foley's campaign platform was unique, she said she would refuse the salary, car, and driver that traditionally came with the position. In addition she proposed evaluating after two years on the job whether the position of Lieutenant Governor should be abolished entirely.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cynthia Needham |first1=Karen Lee Ziner |title=Healey says many states are discussing eliminating the lieutenant governor position |url=https://www.politifact.com/rhode-island/statements/2010/oct/30/robert-healey/healey-says-many-states-are-discussing-eliminating/ |website=politifact.com |publisher=Poynter Institute |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> She was the only candidate in the [[2010 Connecticut gubernatorial election]] who ran for Lieutenant Governor without a gubernatorial running mate. She lost the election to [[Nancy Wyman]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barron |first1=James |title=U.S. Indicts Ex-Connecticut Governor Again |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/11/nyregion/ex-gov-john-rowland-of-connecticut-is-indicted-again.html |website=www.nytimes.com |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Congress ===\nLisa Wilson-Foley ran for the 2012 Congressional Election in [[Connecticut's 5th congressional district]]. Her run was endorsed by a number of prominent local politicians and was considered competitive.<ref>{{cite web |title=Two legislators endorse Wilson-Foley in the 5th |url=https://archives.rep-am.com/2012/01/11/two-legislators-endorse-wilson-foley-in-the-5th/ |website=rep-am.com |publisher=Republican American |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> She declined [[Publicly funded elections|public funding]] for her campaign<ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |first1=CT Mirror |title=Lisa Wilson-Foley announces for lieutenant governor |url=https://ctmirror.org/2010/04/07/lisa-wilson-foley-announces-lieutenant-governor/ |website=ctmirror.org |publisher=The Connecticut News Project |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> and instead loaned her campaign just under a million dollars.<ref name=\"FEC General Counsel's Report\" /> In the Republican Primary she competed against Mark Greenberg, and Justin Bernier and [[Andrew Roraback]]. She was defeated by Roraback but waged a hard-fought campaign in which she and Roraback battled fiercely while largely ignoring the other two candidates.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rennie |first1=Kevin |title=Wilson-Foley in Full Fury. Risks Blow Back With Ferocious Attack on Roraback\u2013For Supporting Death Penalty. |url=https://www.dailyructions.com/wilson-foley-in-full-fury-risks-blow-back-with-ferocious-attack-on-roraback-for-supporting-death-penalty/ |website=dailyructions.com |publisher=Daily Runctions |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> Roraback went on to be narrowly defeated by Democrat [[Elizabeth Esty]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Keating |first1=Christopher |title=Esty Wins, Roraback Concedes After Tight Race For 5th Congressional District |url=https://www.courant.com/politics/hc-ct-5th-district-elizabeth-esty-andrew-roraback--20121101-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> \n\nSoon after her loss her campaign became the subject of state and federal investigations. At the core of the investigations was her relationship with John Rowland.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leigh Cowan |first1=Alison |title=In Connecticut Ex-Governor's Trial, a Window Onto Political Strategizing |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/06/nyregion/in-connecticut-john-g-rowland-ex-governors-trial-a-window-onto-political-strategizing.html |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001011847/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/06/nyregion/in-connecticut-john-g-rowland-ex-governors-trial-a-window-onto-political-strategizing.html |archive-date=1 October 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all |date=2014-09-05 }}</ref> She had hired him to adviser her campaign but because he was a convicted felon and notoriously corrupt she chose to pay him more than US$35,000 through her husband's legitimate businesses in the hopes of avoiding negative publicity. By law all paid campaign staff must be reported, but the Foley-Wilson campaign neglected to report him.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune\" />  Rowland provided fraudulent invoices for services on behalf of the couple's nursing home company as cover for the payments.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Christoffersen |first1=John |title=Guilty pleas in campaign finance scheme linked to ex-Gov. John Rowland |url=https://www.nhregister.com/connecticut/article/Guilty-pleas-in-campaign-finance-scheme-linked-to-11362751.php |website=nhregister.com |publisher=The Associated Press |accessdate=23 April 2019|date=2014-03-31 }}</ref> Prosecutors alleged that Wilson-Foley, Foley, and Rowland engaged in a conspiracy to [[Electoral fraud|steal the election]] along with a number of unindicted co-conspirators.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune\">{{cite web |last1=H. Mahony |first1=Edmund |title=Feds Want Prison For Lisa Wilson-Foley In Rowland Case |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/hc-foley-sentencing-rowland-1231-20141230-story.html |website=chicagotribune.com |publisher=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=27 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Wilson-Foley was sentenced to five months in prison and five months of home confinement.<ref>{{cite web |last1=H. Mahony |first1=Edmund |title=Wilson-Foley Sentenced To 5 Months In Prison |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-lisa-wilson-foley-sentencing-20150324-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=The Hartford Courant |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113082153/http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-lisa-wilson-foley-sentencing-20150324-story.html |archive-date=13 January 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Federal Prosecutors had requested that she spend at least ten months in prison <ref>{{cite web |title=Government recommends prison for Wilson-Foley |url=https://fox61.com/2015/01/02/government-recommends-prison-for-wilson-foley/ |website=fox61.com |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> for her role in leading a \u201cprolonged and calculated effort to defraud voters.\u201d<ref name=\"New Haven Independent\">{{cite web |last1=Leigh Cowan |first1=Alison |title=Crooked Hubby's Deal May Cost Wife Jail Time |url=https://www.newhavenindependent.org/index.php/archives/entry/wilson_foley_sentencing/ |website=newhavenindependent.org |publisher=New Haven Independent |accessdate=27 April 2019|date=2015-01-28 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the charges related to Rowland's contracting she also ran afoul of [[Federal Election Commission]] regulation regarding campaign contributions. The campaign failed to report a $500,000 contribution by Brian Foley to the campaign, instead choosing to report it as Wilson-Foley's own contribution. This violated was discovered when her husband testified as such during his 2014 trial.<ref>{{cite web |title=RE: MUR 6566 |url=https://www.fec.gov/files/legal/murs/current/100487026.pdf |website=fec.gov |publisher=Federal Election Commission |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121055946/https://www.fec.gov/files/legal/murs/current/100487026.pdf |archive-date=21 November 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Brian Foley also used four individuals as straw donors to make donations that in and of themselves exceeded the individual contribution limit of US$2,500 in addition to being illegal due to their duplicitous nature. The straw donor contributions of the four individuals totaled more than US$30,000. These violations are especially egregious as Wilson-Foley also served as the campaign's treasurer.<ref name=\"FEC General Counsel's Report\">{{cite web |title=THIRD GENERAL COUNSEL'S REPORT |url=https://www.fec.gov/files/legal/murs/current/100487029.pdf |website=fec.gov |publisher=Federal Election Commission |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> Foley and Wilson-Foley also used their business resources to directly support the campaign in violation of federal law, members of the Apple Rehab marketing staff were unofficially assigned to the campaign and other staff members got tasked to help personally persuade convention delegates to vote for Wilson-Foley.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune\" />\n\n== Awards and recognitions ==\n* Southern New England Entrepreneur of the Year (1995)<ref name=\"Courant 1996\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[John G. Rowland]]\n* [[2010 Connecticut gubernatorial election]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links == \n* {{URL|http://www.swallowingdiagnostics.com}}\n* {{URL|https://www.apple-rehab.com/AR/}}\n* {{URL|https://www.bluefoxenterprise.com}}\n* {{URL|https://funwhileitlasted.net/2014/02/16/2000-2006-hartford-foxforce/}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilson-Foley, Lisa}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Connecticut Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of campaign finance violations]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century businesswomen]]\n[[Category:21st-century businesswomen]]\n[[Category:Ithaca College alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Connecticut alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lisa Wilson-Foley\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| nationality        = [[United States|American]]\n| citizenship        = [[United States]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Ithaca College]]<br>[[Yale University]]<br>[[University of Connecticut]]\n| occupation         = Entrepreneur\n| party              = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse             = Brian Foley\n| children           = Multiple\n| net worth          = US$23 million (2010)\n}}\n\n'''Lisa Wilson-Foley''' (born approximately 1960) is an entrepreneur, former political candidate, and white collar criminal from the American state of [[Connecticut]]. A serial entrepreneur she formed her first company at 29 and now owns rehabilitation company Allstar Therapy, family entertainment business Blue Fox Enterprises, and medical testing company Swallowing Diagnostics.\n\n== Early life and family ==\nWilson-Foley graduated from [[Farmington High School (Connecticut)|Farmington High School]] in 1977.<ref name=\"Linkedin\" /> Wilson-Foley received a B.S. from Ithaca College in 1981, a masters in Public Health from Yale University 1988, and a degree in Executive Managed Care Division from the University of Connecticut in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet the candidate: Lisa Wilson-Foley |url=https://archives.rep-am.com/2010/08/24/meet-the-candidate-lisa-wilson-foley/ |website=rep-am.com |publisher=Republican American |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> She received her doctorate from University of Montana in 2013. She met her husband Brian Foley while in grad school; he was one of her professors.<ref name=\"Sink Or Swim\"/> Together they have a blended family with seven children.<ref name=\"Watchdog News Hour Interview\" />\n\n== Business career ==\nA serial entrepreneur she formed her first company at 29.<ref name=\"Sink Or Swim\">{{cite book |last1=Priscilla Cale |first1=David C. Tate |title=Sink Or Swim: How Lessons from the Titanic Can Save Your Family Business |date=2011 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |location=Santa Barbara, California |isbn=9780313398346 |pages=140\u2013141}}</ref> In 1997 she sold her original healthcare businesses and as a result of an agreement she was prohibited from re-entering the healthcare field for several years. This forced her to pursue investments in the entertainment field.<ref name=\"Courant 1998\">{{cite web |last1=H. Johnson |first1=Paul |title=A PLACE TO ROCK 'N BOWL |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-1998-02-17-9802170467-story.html |website=www.courant.com |publisher=The Hartford Courant |accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref> She is also involved in her husband's businesses.  At the time of her conviction her personal net worth was estimated to be US$23 million, this is separate from her husband's nine figure net worth.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leigh Cowan |first1=Alison |title=Wilson-Foley given 5-month jail term |url=https://ctmirror.org/2015/03/24/lisa-wilson-foley-gets-5-month-jail-term/ |website=ctmirror.org |publisher=CT Mirror |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622114535/http://ctmirror.org/2015/03/24/lisa-wilson-foley-gets-5-month-jail-term/ |archive-date=22 June 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Many of her businesses are owned through her [[holding company]] LWF Holdings. Her friend [[Janet Peckinpaugh]] served as the marketing director of LWF Holdings.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hebert |first1=Gregory |title=Blue Fox Rock'n Bowl Cuts Ribbon on Laser Tag Arena |url=https://patch.com/connecticut/simsbury/blue-fox-rock-n-bowl-cuts-ribbon-on-laser-tag-arena |website=patch.com |publisher=Patch |accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> In 2010 her campaign claimed that she directly employed 500 people and had hosted a group of 15 Kenyan entrepreneurs on a tour of Connecticut.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wilson-Foley |title=Lisa Wilson-Foley, Candidate for Lieutenant Governor, Hosts 15 Kenyan Entrepreneurs |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/lisa-wilson-foley-candidate-for-lieutenant-governor-hosts-15-kenyan-entrepreneurs-92491829.html |website=prnewswire.com |publisher=Wilson-Foley 2010 |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Allstar Therapy===\nAllstar Therapy provides occupational, speech and physical rehabilitation in health care facilities throughout Connecticut, Massachusetts and Rhode Island. Allstar Therapy was sold in 2016.<ref name=\"Linkedin\">{{cite web |title=Lisa Wilson Foley |url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/lisa-wilson-foley-2a285b3 |website=www.linkedin.com |publisher=Linkedin |accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Blue Fox Enterprises === \nIn 1998 she acquired the Simsbury Bowling Center and renamed it Blue Fox Rock 'N Bowl and renovated  it emphasize a family friendly atmosphere.<ref name=\"Courant 1998\" /> In 1999 she acquired the Copper Hill Golf Club for $1.3m renaming it Fox Run at Copper Hill.<ref name=\"Courant 1999\">{{cite web |last1=Lemos |first1=Phil |title=GOLF COURSE GETS A NEW OWNER |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-1999-01-15-9901150564-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=The Hartford Courant |accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> The club was sold in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jensen |first1=Tim |title=West Suffield Resident Breathing New Life Into Copper Hill Golf Club |url=https://patch.com/connecticut/suffield/west-suffield-resident-breathing-new-life-into-copper-hill-golf-club |website=patch.com |publisher=Patch |accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref> The company recently sold three Victorian Bed and Breakfasts in [[Newport, RI]].<ref name=\"Linkedin\" /> \n\n==== Blue Fox Run Golf Course ====\nBlue Fox Run is a 27-hole golf course owned by Wilson-Foley notable for being the first in the country to offer onsite [[childcare]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lisa Wilson-Foley - Republican candidate for Lieutenant Governor |url=https://www.registercitizen.com/news/article/Lisa-Wilson-Foley-12112196.php |website=registercitizen.com |publisher=Hearst Media |accessdate=23 April 2019|date=2010-08-07 }}</ref> In 1996 she purchased the property, then known as the Bel Compo Golf Course and having only 18 holes, for US$3.5m with her husband purchasing 55 adjoining acres.<ref name=\"Courant 1996\">{{cite web |last1=Stowe |first1=Stacey |title=AVON PAIR TO BUY BEL COMPO COURSE |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-1996-09-30-9609300413-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=The Hartford Courant |accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref> In 1997 Wilson-Foley successfully applied to rezone 15 of their acres to office park, the parcel was subsequently developed with three office buildings having been built as of 2012.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sawyer |first1=Jessie |title=Commission Rejects Golf Club's Proposal to Rezone Open Space Land |url=https://patch.com/connecticut/avon/1m-homes-may-be-built-on-excess-avon-golf-club-land |website=patch.com |publisher=Patch |accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Hartford FoxForce ===\nIn 1999 Wilson-Foley and her husband franchised the [[World TeamTennis]] team Hartford FoxForce in [[Hartford, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bailer |first1=Darice |title=Team Tennis Finds a Home in Hartford |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/07/23/nyregion/team-tennis-finds-a-home-in-hartford.html?searchResultPosition=19 |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=26 April 2019|date=2000-07-23 }}</ref> FoxForce's first drafted player was [[Monica Seles]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Garber |first1=Greg |title=SELES FIRST MEMBER OF FOXFORCE |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2000-04-04-0004051707-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> In 2001 the team fielded brothers [[Murphy Jensen]] and [[Luke Jensen]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gonzalez |first1=Roberto |title=FOXFORCE PUT JENSENS TOGETHER |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2001-04-12-0104122097-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=The Hartford Courant |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> Over the years the team fielded other well known players such as [[Bethanie Mattek-Sands]], [[Boris Becker]], and [[James Blake (tennis)|James Blake]]. The team played first at Hartford's 3,000 seat [[State Arsenal and Armory]] and later at a 2,500 seat outdoor stadium Wilson-Foley had built at her Blue Fox Run golf course. The Foley's shut the team down in 2007 due to a lack of corporate sponsorships.<ref>{{cite web |title=2000-2006 Hartford FoxForce |url=https://funwhileitlasted.net/2014/02/16/2000-2006-hartford-foxforce/ |website=funwhileitlasted.net |publisher=funwhileitlasted.net |accessdate=27 April 2019|date=2014-02-16 }}</ref> Mark Foley's [[Connecticut Pride]] also used the State Arsenal and Armory as a venue from 1993-2000.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hasty|first1=Roy|title=Connecticut Pride; Lion To Be King Where Hellcats Once Ruled|url=http://articles.courant.com/1995-08-11/sports/9508110481_1_aetna-life-casualty-tyler-jones-hartford-s-continental-basketball-association|accessdate=April 30, 2019|work=Hartford Courant|date=August 11, 1995|location=Hartford, Connecticut}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nBefore her conviction Wilson-Foley served as the vice-chair of the board at [[The Bushnell Center for the Performing Arts]].<ref name= \"Watchdog News Hour Interview\">{{cite web |last1=George |first1=Gombassy |title=Watchdog News Hour: Lisa Wilson-Foley |url=http://ctwatchdog.com/health/watchdog-news-hour-lisa-wilson-foley |website=ctwatchdog.com |publisher=CT Watchdog |accessdate=23 April 2019|date=2011-05-16 }}</ref> Previously she served on the board of the [[Renbrook School]] and the [[American School for the Deaf]].<ref name=\"Watchdog News Hour Interview\" />\n\n== Political campaigns ==\nShe is a political protege of former [[Governor of Connecticut]] [[John G. Rowland]] who called her \u201cgrasshopper\u201d during his political tutelage.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Leigh Cowan |first1=Alison |title=Wilson-Foley given 5-month jail term |url=https://ctmirror.org/2015/03/24/lisa-wilson-foley-gets-5-month-jail-term/ |website=ctmirror.org |publisher=CT Mirror |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622114535/http://ctmirror.org/2015/03/24/lisa-wilson-foley-gets-5-month-jail-term/ |archive-date=22 June 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \n\n=== Lieutenant Governor ===\nIn 2010 Lisa Wilson-Foley announced that she was running for [[Lieutenant Governor of Connecticut]] as a Republican.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stewart |first1=Christine |title=Republican Announces For Lt. Gov. |url=https://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/archives/entry/republican_announces_for_lt._gov/ |website=ctnewsjunkie.com |publisher=CT News Junkie |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> Wilson-Foley's campaign platform was unique, she said she would refuse the salary, car, and driver that traditionally came with the position. In addition she proposed evaluating after two years on the job whether the position of Lieutenant Governor should be abolished entirely.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cynthia Needham |first1=Karen Lee Ziner |title=Healey says many states are discussing eliminating the lieutenant governor position |url=https://www.politifact.com/rhode-island/statements/2010/oct/30/robert-healey/healey-says-many-states-are-discussing-eliminating/ |website=politifact.com |publisher=Poynter Institute |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> She was the only candidate in the [[2010 Connecticut gubernatorial election]] who ran for Lieutenant Governor without a gubernatorial running mate. She lost the election to [[Nancy Wyman]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barron |first1=James |title=U.S. Indicts Ex-Connecticut Governor Again |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/11/nyregion/ex-gov-john-rowland-of-connecticut-is-indicted-again.html |website=www.nytimes.com |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Congress ===\nLisa Wilson-Foley ran for the 2012 Congressional Election in [[Connecticut's 5th congressional district]]. Her run was endorsed by a number of prominent local politicians and was considered competitive.<ref>{{cite web |title=Two legislators endorse Wilson-Foley in the 5th |url=https://archives.rep-am.com/2012/01/11/two-legislators-endorse-wilson-foley-in-the-5th/ |website=rep-am.com |publisher=Republican American |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> She declined [[Publicly funded elections|public funding]] for her campaign<ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |first1=CT Mirror |title=Lisa Wilson-Foley announces for lieutenant governor |url=https://ctmirror.org/2010/04/07/lisa-wilson-foley-announces-lieutenant-governor/ |website=ctmirror.org |publisher=The Connecticut News Project |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> and instead loaned her campaign just under a million dollars.<ref name=\"FEC General Counsel's Report\" /> In the Republican Primary she competed against Mark Greenberg, and Justin Bernier and [[Andrew Roraback]]. She was defeated by Roraback but waged a hard-fought campaign in which she and Roraback battled fiercely while largely ignoring the other two candidates.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rennie |first1=Kevin |title=Wilson-Foley in Full Fury. Risks Blow Back With Ferocious Attack on Roraback\u2013For Supporting Death Penalty. |url=https://www.dailyructions.com/wilson-foley-in-full-fury-risks-blow-back-with-ferocious-attack-on-roraback-for-supporting-death-penalty/ |website=dailyructions.com |publisher=Daily Runctions |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> Roraback went on to be narrowly defeated by Democrat [[Elizabeth Esty]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Keating |first1=Christopher |title=Esty Wins, Roraback Concedes After Tight Race For 5th Congressional District |url=https://www.courant.com/politics/hc-ct-5th-district-elizabeth-esty-andrew-roraback--20121101-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> \n\nSoon after her loss her campaign became the subject of state and federal investigations. At the core of the investigations was her relationship with John Rowland.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leigh Cowan |first1=Alison |title=In Connecticut Ex-Governor's Trial, a Window Onto Political Strategizing |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/06/nyregion/in-connecticut-john-g-rowland-ex-governors-trial-a-window-onto-political-strategizing.html |newspaper=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001011847/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/06/nyregion/in-connecticut-john-g-rowland-ex-governors-trial-a-window-onto-political-strategizing.html |archive-date=1 October 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all |date=2014-09-05 }}</ref> She had hired him to adviser her campaign but because he was a convicted felon and notoriously corrupt she chose to pay him more than US$35,000 through her husband's legitimate businesses in the hopes of avoiding negative publicity. By law all paid campaign staff must be reported, but the Foley-Wilson campaign neglected to report him.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune\" />  Rowland provided fraudulent invoices for services on behalf of the couple's nursing home company as cover for the payments.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Christoffersen |first1=John |title=Guilty pleas in campaign finance scheme linked to ex-Gov. John Rowland |url=https://www.nhregister.com/connecticut/article/Guilty-pleas-in-campaign-finance-scheme-linked-to-11362751.php |website=nhregister.com |publisher=The Associated Press |accessdate=23 April 2019|date=2014-03-31 }}</ref> Prosecutors alleged that Wilson-Foley, Foley, and Rowland engaged in a conspiracy to [[Electoral fraud|steal the election]] along with a number of unindicted co-conspirators.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune\">{{cite web |last1=H. Mahony |first1=Edmund |title=Feds Want Prison For Lisa Wilson-Foley In Rowland Case |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/hc-foley-sentencing-rowland-1231-20141230-story.html |website=chicagotribune.com |publisher=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=27 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Wilson-Foley was sentenced to five months in prison and five months of home confinement.<ref>{{cite web |last1=H. Mahony |first1=Edmund |title=Wilson-Foley Sentenced To 5 Months In Prison |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-lisa-wilson-foley-sentencing-20150324-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=The Hartford Courant |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113082153/http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-lisa-wilson-foley-sentencing-20150324-story.html |archive-date=13 January 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Federal Prosecutors had requested that she spend at least ten months in prison <ref>{{cite web |title=Government recommends prison for Wilson-Foley |url=https://fox61.com/2015/01/02/government-recommends-prison-for-wilson-foley/ |website=fox61.com |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> for her role in leading a \u201cprolonged and calculated effort to defraud voters.\u201d<ref name=\"New Haven Independent\">{{cite web |last1=Leigh Cowan |first1=Alison |title=Crooked Hubby's Deal May Cost Wife Jail Time |url=https://www.newhavenindependent.org/index.php/archives/entry/wilson_foley_sentencing/ |website=newhavenindependent.org |publisher=New Haven Independent |accessdate=27 April 2019|date=2015-01-28 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the charges related to Rowland's contracting she also ran afoul of [[Federal Election Commission]] regulation regarding campaign contributions. The campaign failed to report a $500,000 contribution by Brian Foley to the campaign, instead choosing to report it as Wilson-Foley's own contribution. This violated was discovered when her husband testified as such during his 2014 trial.<ref>{{cite web |title=RE: MUR 6566 |url=https://www.fec.gov/files/legal/murs/current/100487026.pdf |website=fec.gov |publisher=Federal Election Commission |accessdate=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121055946/https://www.fec.gov/files/legal/murs/current/100487026.pdf |archive-date=21 November 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Brian Foley also used four individuals as straw donors to make donations that in and of themselves exceeded the individual contribution limit of US$2,500 in addition to being illegal due to their duplicitous nature. The straw donor contributions of the four individuals totaled more than US$30,000. These violations are especially egregious as Wilson-Foley also served as the campaign's treasurer.<ref name=\"FEC General Counsel's Report\">{{cite web |title=THIRD GENERAL COUNSEL'S REPORT |url=https://www.fec.gov/files/legal/murs/current/100487029.pdf |website=fec.gov |publisher=Federal Election Commission |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> Foley and Wilson-Foley also used their business resources to directly support the campaign in violation of federal law, members of the Apple Rehab marketing staff were unofficially assigned to the campaign and other staff members got tasked to help personally persuade convention delegates to vote for Wilson-Foley.<ref name=\"Chicago Tribune\" />\n\n== Awards and recognitions ==\n* Southern New England Entrepreneur of the Year (1995)<ref name=\"Courant 1996\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[John G. Rowland]]\n* [[2010 Connecticut gubernatorial election]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links == \n* {{URL|http://www.swallowingdiagnostics.com}}\n* {{URL|https://www.apple-rehab.com/AR/}}\n* {{URL|https://www.bluefoxenterprise.com}}\n* {{URL|https://funwhileitlasted.net/2014/02/16/2000-2006-hartford-foxforce/}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilson-Foley, Lisa}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Connecticut Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of campaign finance violations]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century businesswomen]]\n[[Category:21st-century businesswomen]]\n[[Category:Ithaca College alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Connecticut alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Trillfendi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lisa_Wilson-Foley"}
